<h1 class="title">AdvantagesOfJetDeClustering</h1>
<p>
Jet (de)clustering is similar in spirit to hemisphere mixing, but some potential improvements
</p>
<ol class="org-ol">
<li>Scrambling the substructure is done through sampling the PDFs templates instead of directly reusing jets in other observed events.  This leads to a big statistical gain from factorizing the <a href="splittingtemplates-20250504111010.html#ID-84055C72-DBD2-4091-B41C-D85A63AF9A1B">SplittingTemplates</a>.</li>
<li>The algorithm has better scaling with dataset size. Goes like O(N) not O(N<sup>2</sup>),  from the nested loops over hemisphere for each event.</li>
<li>It is less ad-hoc: there is no need to define a metric between hemispheres.</li>
<li>Better treatment of the additional jet activity <a href="isr_fsr_jet_discernmentinjetdeclustering-20250504111327.html#ID-4818B79E-AA18-4820-8817-73CEF3441616">ISR-FSR-jet-DiscernmentInJetDeClustering</a>.  Can decluster iteratively with splitting functions (can be done separately for g→bb and b→bg splittings see:[[<a href="btagsasaquarkgluontag-20250504111118.html#ID-8CBCCBAA-E746-470B-93DA-CE0E76525D57">BTagsAsAQuarkGluonTag</a>)</li>
<li>Can also potentially be applied in the boosted regime by (de)clustering the constituent sub-jets directly.</li>
</ol>



